<h1>Quick stop and then dinner</h1>
<p>Unlike last summer, we didn't have time to hike up Seongsan Ilchulbong (a UNESCO World Heritage site), but we did make a quick stop for some photos. If you go there just before sunset, you can get some Instagram-worthy shots.</p>
<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/ryucave/image/upload/v1598754905/Day-5-Jeju/5-crater_gaeot6.jpg" alt='crater' />
<p>For dinner, we met up with one of my old friends who now lives in Jeju. He picked a seafood place on the eastern coast of the island. The owner-couple are, like most Jeju folks, just genuinely kind and warm-hearted. And their little Jindo dog is also as calm and laid-back his the owners. The kids really enjoyed playing with little Jindo (not his actual name).</p>
<p>We had quite a feast. We started with some beef on the grill with lettuce and sesame leaves. Then we had some raw fish and a big pot of fish stew. The fish was actually caught by my friend. The way they cooked the fish stew resulted in the most tender fish I've ever had. Really delicious.</p>

